Write a shell script that monitors a given directory for new files. When a new file is detected:
Log the filename and timestamp into a log file.
Compress the file into a .tar.gz archive.
Move the archive into a backup directory.
Ensure the script runs continuously and handles errors gracefully (e.g., if the backup directory doesn’t exist).
#!/bin/bash

WATCH_DIR="$HOME"                # safer than /home
BACKUP_DIR="$HOME/backup"        # writable directory
LOG_FILE="$HOME/log.txt"

mkdir -p "$BACKUP_DIR"
new_files=$(find "$WATCH_DIR" -type f -mmin -5)  # files modified in last 5 minutes

if [ -n "$new_files" ]; then
    for i in $new_files; do
        echo "$i - $(date)" >> "$LOG_FILE"
        tar -czf "$BACKUP_DIR/$(basename "$i").tar.gz" "$i"
    done
fi
